segments.text: No, sir.
No, sir.
I must have been before my time or after.
Let's see.
Did you all go to any campus dances?
No, sir.
As a matter of fact, Richard and I never did go to dance.
See, I don't dance.
I'm a teetotaler.
I don't drink and I don't smoke.
I don't go to dances because my grandmother raised me, you see.
She was really strict and she didn't want me to get mixed up with the wrong people and start drinking with them and all this.
I share those practices with you.
And then my wife was brought up with the Baptists in Beeville, and you know, the Baptists don't dance either.
Now, there had been some veterans' temporary housing down here on this side of the football stadium.
That had been removed by the time you all got here.
There were some temporary, where G. Raleigh White Coliseum is now, there were some temporary veteran's houses in 46 and 47, but those were gone by the time y'all got here.
As you are going on toward that major in animal husbandry, who did you turn to for advice and counsel?
Who gave, who told you what courses to take?
Nobody told me what courses to take, no.
Rachel had a brother that was working for the BVL Experimental Station, and he was an animal husband and an agronomer, okay?
And in conversations with him and the other two that were attending here,
I was interested in agronomy, but then I was afraid that I would not be able to pass maybe
the chemistry or the math that went along with it.
So I had to select something that I knew I could pass.
And so I started considering getting a liberal arts or a business.
And business looked better.
And so then because of my experiences and the work I used to do,
I thought I wanted to major in marketing with a minor in English.
Who advised you to do that?
Well, to tell you the truth, nobody.
Oh, okay.
I took the catalog and I was going through it.
If I want to major here, what question do I have to take?
Can I pass them?
I was looking back.
hey, I was 32 years old, I was out of high school, and I was a high school dropout.
So I had, there was some disadvantages there, but I wanted to be sure after, you know, getting rid of my house and furniture and so forth, and for me to flunk out again, no.
I gotta make a go of it, and I made that decision myself, see.
All right, now, as you began your senior year,
When did you buy that ring?
Oh, I didn't buy the ring.
One of the brothers, Rachel's brothers that had already graduated, he was a petroleum engineer with Atlantic Refining.
He was nice enough to buy my ring and get Rachel her ring.
I want to tell you something, you won't believe it.
I still have the ring.
This is the original one.
And I learned to take it off when I wash my hands or when I'm working, so it won't bleed.
And then I take some India ink and I cover it, then I let it dry, and I take a damp rag and clean it off.
So it still looks almost new.
Yeah.
And some people look at that, is that a new one?
No.
I didn't ask.
My brother-in-law, his name was Alvino, Alvino Reyes, he told Rachel he paid $29.50 for this ring.
Oh my, my.
Believe it or not.
Now, his son, he had a son that was handicapped, and I decided to return the favor.
And I told him, I said, look Bubba, I want to pay for your record.
Oh he was pleased.
So I shelled out $175.
I did that gladly really.
But I don't know what that costs now.
Do you have any ring stories?
Have you ever lost your ring and found it in somebody?
Or have you ever been somewhere on the other side of the world and somebody saw that Aggie ring?
No, sir, I never lost it.
I made sure that I put it in my pocket.
Well, even to this day, people see my ring, they say,
Hey, I just saw your ring.
And before they could say anything, I went to whip out and meet them.
And here we are.
And right now, I'm retired, and I'm a volunteer at a cafeteria-style restaurant that belongs to the First Baptist Church back in San Antonio.
And Southwestern Bell has a monster building just about two blocks away.
I was on the Southwestern Bell board for 17 years.
So there's a bunch of Aggies that are working there and they come over there and eat.
And I'll bust tables you know and do arching in.
And when I fill up their glasses with tea, it starts again.
So I greet them.
Hi Aggie.
And people turn around.
Yes sir, that ring touches something.
I wear this one, that's my Masonic ring.
And some guy said, look, I'm wearing the same kind of ring you've got.
But that's, I don't recall going somewhere in, you know, a way, or just nothing of any importance.
that I know of that I have for you.
All right, let's see.
Your senior year, you mention in here that your son starts school and your wife got sick.
Oh, yeah.
And so you had to double up and you moved to a dormitory.
What was it like for an old man to live with those undergraduates?
I went in with a Nunn-Regg student.
He was real nice.
And we had to share the room.
And I had the top bunk and he had the lower bunk.

and uh he was uh how old was he he must have been uh oh about 24. no he was a veteran also i don't know i don't recall that he was but he was not in the corps and he was getting his degree in accounting did you eat in the in the sabisa then uh no oh
I, you see, the MSC had a place to eat, and I remember I used to eat basket burgers.
Give me a basket with a hamburger and some french fries.
Right, right.
Let's see, then you didn't buy senior boots since you weren't in the Corps, and you didn't go to final review.
But you did go to commencement.
Oh, yes.
Where was commencement held?
At Kyle Field.
At Kyle Field.
Yes, sir.
Do you remember who the speaker was?
No, sir.
Most of us don't remember who the speaker was.
Who came?
What family came for your commencement?
My mother and two of my sisters.
That was all.
And then, of course, Rachel was there.
And I remember her.
When I went across the platform to get there, my sister said, that's my daddy.
But look, before that, there used to be a fellow, his name was Don Harrison, and he used to work at a parts department with me.
He was old.
And he had two brothers that owned a clothing store.
in San Antonio called Fomby's, and it stood for men.
And he went to work for them, and he was a front man.
He joined the Chamber of Commerce and he joined all these, you know, and tried to get people to come and patronize his store.
So I went to my trust and said, I'm graduating, I don't have clothes, and I need a suit of clothes.
I can't pay you.
But as soon as I get a job, I'll pay you."
He said, ah, bonk.
He took over there.
I got a brand new dark blue suit.
And he wrote something on there.
It's this.
And he gave it to me.
Otherwise, I didn't have a suit of clothes.
And so that's part of our graduation.

and uh it was it was great all right as you walked across that stage that day what feelings did you have in your heart oh i said i was relieved of all the pressure i was living under and this kind of thing that uh you know uh
You don't have to repeat this, but my wife had hemorrhoids.
And one of the hemorrhoids had some kind of a knot in it or something that her doctor, Dr. Lancaster, said that this could be something bad, and I think we better get it out of the way.
And so I had some health insurance with me.
I can't remember the name, but they called him Tack.
He had an office in Northgate, you know, T-A-C-K. And it was that coverage I had that got my wife at the hospital there in Bealeville.
And she, I was, I was sending her the, I was getting, I was sending her $60 of my $120.
And now, see, I was the guy and I was, my gross was $80 a month.
And of course, for the end of the month came by, I didn't get paid at the end of the month.
You had to wait about two weeks.
So, and I was sending the whole check to them in New York.
I says, listen, you living over there with your mother, recuperating?
And I don't want to hear any of your sisters or brothers saying that you were a charity case.
You pay your mama and you tell her that, look, this is all I've got, but I want to pay for my food and for Robert's food and whatever.
So they wouldn't come later on and criticize me for leaving my wife over there and let her mother take care of her.
As you were getting ready to graduate, what kind of preparation did you think A&M had given you for the real world?
Well.
How well prepared were you?
I was prepared.
And when I went for the job interviews, I would get
uh, offers for out of state, out of town.
And my wife had tap roots in San Antonio, New York, and she didn't want to move anywhere.
I said, oh, good, you know.
And, uh, so I said, well, I'd have to find something here in San Antonio.
And, uh, she says, all right, um, oh.
I said, let's see, uh, what the Lord wants to do with us and, uh, see if we'll go from here.
So I looked around and I got this, the best job I had was working on it at Lackland, civilian position.
And Lackland had a requirement that you had to know this and this and this and this, or one year of college.
That's a snap.
And this was a big operation.
The training needs a vision.
Because Lackland, at the time I was there, was like a little college.
Oh, it was huge.
And the trainees weren't in there for training.
They had three training bases, one in Rome, New York, one in California, and then the one there in San Antonio.
So they closed these other two and left Lackland.
And they had a dental school.
They had a police school.
They had .
So the division would make custom-made teaching aids, all kinds of manuals, instruction manuals, building ceremonies, and whatever the instructors wanted besides the language school.
They had a language school where they would teach English to these foreign pilots.
So someday, we would need them as our allies.
And the trainees also made language trainers.
You're familiar with a language trainer, where you're watching it and hearing it.
And it was nice, and security.
My wife was satisfied.
Then I got the opportunity to go to Kelly Air Force Base and it was a little bit more responsibility and it was a better job.
Since I had all this experience with parts for General Motors,
We didn't have a buyer that could buy aircraft parts.
So I got in there and they shipped me off to Fort Lee, Virginia.
Six weeks in a preparatory school for buyers.
And I came back.
And let me see.
I had gone to the office, and all of a sudden there was a dead silence.
What happened?
The news came on that President Kennedy had been shot.
Oh, my God, this would have to happen.
Well, anyway, I stayed all night at Kelly and worked up from a bar to a contracting officer.
with a warrant and it was the General's approval and one from up in command level and I had no limitations and it was good until I retired.
As you look back, what did A&M for you, what did A&M do well?
So get a job, and when you got it, you worked on it to completion, and that it would be done right.
And they wouldn't settle for anything else.
And that stayed with me.
And so in my work, I went from A to Z, so that if my supervisors ever
Well, they couldn't question me because it was all right there, ready to go.
And complete it to a successful end and don't mess around and do it right.
If you had all of the people that were at A&M when you were here, if all of them were here today, which ones would you most want to thank?
To what people from that time are you most grateful?
Tom Putty.
You see, maybe I shouldn't say this, and you don't have to, but when I applied to the employment office, there was an old gentleman, you know, he had a big hat like he was a retired rancher.
And he says, I can't consider you for a job.
He says, you're a veteran, and you're getting $120 a month.
He says, I've got some kids coming out of high school that don't have a penny.
He says, I've got to give them priority.
So I can't offer you a job.
Oh, boy, that's when I started.
And I went to Chevrolet dealer Brian Carpenter.
I got all the help I need.
Well, how about part-time?
Somebody take inventory or something.
And I went to Caldwell, same way.
I was just about to give up.
So I went back to meet Mr. Putty.
And he turned things around for me.
And I said, hey, let's.
Are there any teachers or advisors that you'd also want to thank?
Any faculty?
Any staff?
Yes.
One was my English professor, Mr., and then there was, I can't think of his name, but you remember Mr. Esten?
C.K.
Esten.
Yeah, he used to, him, I had him for English.
And he made me give an oral report, see?
and he liked it.
He came over and he put his arm around me and we were good friends from then on.
And let's see, I'm trying to think.
Those were the only two, sir.
What is it that builds Aggie spirit?
What causes those feelings?
Well, in my experience,
If I had something to do with another guy, he was an Aggie.
And I let him know I was an Aggie, too.
That friendship was good together, see?
And I knew that any dealings I had or any assistance I needed from a fellow Aggie, that I would get it.
That if my car broke down on the highway, which it did,
A bunch of Aggies in the corner had stopped.
What can I do to help you?
Do you need a flat fixed or whatever?
And I knew that there was a binding thing there between Aggies, and I knew that if I had to deal with another Aggie for whatever, I was in need, that I could expect some form of help.
What causes the Aggies, though, to be helpful to each other?
What is it that happens while they're in school here?
It's hard to say.
I mean, words fail me.
If there's a place that's owned by an Aggie,
If I let them know, hey, I'm an Aggie, he will drop the restriction and it's a way of getting in or getting to know the person.
We're given help to achieve what I'm trying to get or go for, and I can expect friendship
and help that I wouldn't get from somebody else that was not an Aggie.
Let me give you a for instance.
My brother Bert, I mean my brother-in-law Bert, he was a cattle auctioneer, and he had to go to Montana for a cattle sale.
And it was dark, you know,
He was a stranger up there.
He didn't know nobody.
When he goes to the stockyards, there was a bunch of Aggies over there, agricultural people.
And when Bert went over there to meet him, and he found out that there were Aggies, you know, he changed the whole thing.
Anything he needed, he got it, because those Aggies would help him.
And Bertone says, that goes on everywhere, in civilian life and in the military.
And my son, he goes back and forth, and he meets Aggies all over.
And they all, a lot of them come here for legal advice.
If you could advise the leaders of Texas A&M today, what advice would you give them?
to continue and enlarge on the friendship and the camaraderie of all Aggies.
I say that because Plurton Vandiver, he wanted to do away with the Corps.
And I said, well, he's crazy.
I said, the Morrill Act says A&M is going to be put up there because we need a school of agriculture.
There was no other place.
And in addition to that, it says there will be military training at that place.
So Mr. Vandiver cannot do away with it.
And we're going to have people like that, sir, that are going to stop certain traditions.
And I want to tell those people, don't listen to that crap.
I say, you keep this thing going, and it's the only one in the world that's like this, that I know of.
And you keep that going, and then if there's hostilities come up, who's going to get the first call?
A&M.
So it behooves you to just make no changes and improve on it.
All right, we're almost through with the questions I've thought of.
Have you thought of some things we've left out we should have covered?
No, sir.
All right, then among the last questions, what difference has it made in your life that you attended Texas A&M?
We met a lot of people in high places, especially my wife.
My wife is a gung-ho Aggie, I tell you.
And we belong to the San Antonio A&M Club, and she belongs to the A&M Mothers.
And you don't have to put this on there.
She was president of the federation.
Mm-hm.
The whole state, plus our organization in Louisiana and someplace else.
And this is just between us.
Bound to doles.
was the biggest crook, in my opinion, when it deals with trying to sell their wares without competition.
And Bob Smith, I hate his guts for what he did.
So he wanted to set up a place, a cafeteria, a dining hall.
and set it here on a compass.
And just before that, A&M had gotten a lot of publicity on the way our dining halls were being run by these people that were good.
Among the best in the nation.
The best in the nation.
And Mr. Bob Smith was going to do it the other way, see.
Now, we didn't know about this until the kids were riding home.
I need more money.
Why?
Well, the price of food's going to go up and all this.
So Margaret Freeman, Margaret Freeman was the president of the Federation, and her wife was there to help her.
They said, hey, that's a bunch of bull.
So those two ladies questioned Mr. Bob Smith and who was the president, I mean the chairman of the regents.
He's a lawyer.
I don't know, because there are a bunch of lawyers.
Well, he was the chairman at the time.
He was in on that deal.
And they started asking questions, and Bob Smith couldn't give the answers.
Then the governor, that woman, what was her name?
Ann Richards.
Ann Richards.
She got wind of it.
Bob Smith went to her and said, you know, there's two girls over there.
really nitpicking me and I don't have the answers.
And they were getting liquor up there for certain people, you know, to benefit this chairman and Bob Smith.
So they did enough digging, digging, digging, until something happened.
And then Bob Smith was okay.
All because of Margaret Freeman and Rachel Gonzalez.
If they hadn't done that, I don't know where we'd be.
This is the kind of thing I'm saying, hey, all this is no good.
Get it out and prove anything.
So I just, I can't think of this chairman's name.
He's an attorney.
In Houston.
He got out.
He resigned.
Otherwise, you couldn't imagine what was going on.
So my wife,
knows a lot of A&M mothers all over the state.
And she's just nutty.
She's crazy about A&M.
And you better not say anything ugly.
And sometimes we'll go to some meeting and the speaker says, well I want to start, I want to tell you a naggy joke.
And I'm like, no you won't.
I don't want to hear no naggy jokes.
You get down to business.
And the speaker, you know, he don't want to say, he doesn't say the actual.
That's how she loves A&M, see.
And then it flows to me and my son the same way.
Don't say nothing bad about A&M.
Next to last question.
Somebody walks up to you and gives you a check for a million dollars with one condition.
You must pass it on to Texas A&M, but you get to decide how it would be used.
